speaker: A

text: So the structure that we've come up with is that the DAC would actually be a captive of a charitable organization. So in the US, if we do it there, a 501, or if in England, a community interest company, so there's no shareholdings there. But what you do is you have boards of directors who are obliged to carry out their functions in accordance with the organization's purposes. So there's no share ownership. But what we do is we're going to create a mechanism where people are able to trustlessly communicate their wishes and their views, weighted to a certain extent on their reputation within the community. And the board will then be obliged by entering into a trustee to consider those decisions in making its own decisions. And the real benefit to that is that there's no way you can really fraudulently build a sort of political or policy consensus, because you can see, because all the instructions are trustless, who's done what, how, what they've said, and the board can't then turn around and say, well, let's say the community says, we want the board of the association to support, I don't know, let's say support law reform. We want this particular money laundering provision to be opposed. So someone puts it to a vote. The community then says, right, cool. They vote in favor of it. That message is trustlessly generated by the voting DAC. The board then sees it, and then the board really can be held to account if they turn around and go, no, we're not actually going to resource this. The community can say, hold on a second, you had a consensus. Can you please explain to us why you haven't done that? And so more traditional mechanisms, polling online, you can spam, that. You can create spam accounts, sock puppets. When you start doing it, and building in costs on ethereum and start using crypto ledgers for this purpose, that becomes much, much harder to do.
